<div class='communityQuestionAndAnswer'>
<div class='communityQuestion'>
<div class='questionText'>
<a href="/questions/1875058-does-anyone-know-why-the-series-is-called">Does anyone know why the series is called Diogenes? I don&#39;t normally read books like these but I&#39;m a little intrigued by the reference to the cynic/pre-stoic philosopher. I&#39;m curious if there is a theme there or if there is no apparent connection to ancient cynic/stoic philosophy.</a>
</div>
<div class='communityQAFooter questionFooter'>
<ul class='questionFooterActions'>
<li class='footerItem like'>
<span class='likeItContainer' id='like_container_community_question_1875058'><a rel="nofollow" class="jsLike like_it" href="https://www.goodreads.com/user/new?remember=true&amp;return_url=%2Fbook%2Fshow%2F136637.Brimstone">like</a></span>

</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionTimestamp'>
<a href="/questions/1875058-does-anyone-know-why-the-series-is-called">one year ago</a>
</li>
<li class='footerItem communityQuestionPermalink'>
<a href="/questions/1875058-does-anyone-know-why-the-series-is-called">Add your answer</a>
</li>
</ul>
</div>

</div>
<div class='allCommunityAnswers'>
<div class='communityAnswer'>
<div class='communityAnswerBody'>
<div class='answererUserIcon'>
<a class="leftAlignedImage userPhoto" href="/user/show/75879168-vasilis"><img alt="" src="https://i.gr-assets.com/images/S/compressed.photo.goodreads.com/users/1588764664i/75879168._UX100_CR0,16,100,100_.jpg" /></a>
</div>
<div class='communityAnswerTextContainer'>
<span class='communityAnswererName'>
<a href="/user/show/75879168-vasilis">Vasilis</a>
</span>
<span class='communityAnswerText'>
<span class="expandableContainer"><span class="truncatedContent">This is the first book in which Diogenes (Pendergast&apos;s evil/genious brother), is mentioned. He plays no role in the story of the book, but I suppose i<a class="jsShow showAction" href="#">…more</a></span><span class="fullContent">This is the first book in which Diogenes (Pendergast's evil/genious brother), is mentioned. He plays no role in the story of the book, but I suppose it was just an introduction to him in view of his involvement in later books.<a class="jsHide hideAction" href="#">(less)</a></span></span>
</span>
</div>
</div>
